"Hu Z.-Z., Bengtsson L., Roeckner E., Christoph M., Bacher A.Oberhuber J.M.","Impact of global warming on the interannual and interdecadal climate modes in a coupled GCM",2001,"Climate Dynamics","17","5-6",,"361","374",,,,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-0034824684&partnerID=40&md5=db5b9b56131220e943d470e8c6d2e29c","Ctr. Ocean-Land-Atmosphere Stud., 4041 Powder Mill Road, Calverton, MD 20705, United States","Hu, Z.-Z., Ctr. Ocean-Land-Atmosphere Stud., 4041 Powder Mill Road, Calverton, MD 20705, United States; Bengtsson, L., Ctr. Ocean-Land-Atmosphere Stud., 4041 Powder Mill Road, Calverton, MD 20705, United States; Roeckner, E., Ctr. Ocean-Land-Atmosphere Stud., 4041 Powder Mill Road, Calverton, MD 20705, United States; Christoph, M., Ctr. Ocean-Land-Atmosphere Stud., 4041 Powder Mill Road, Calverton, MD 20705, United States; Bacher A.Oberhuber, J.M., Ctr. Ocean-Land-Atmosphere Stud., 4041 Powder Mill Road, Calverton, MD 20705, United States","In this study, we investigated the impact of global warming on the variabilities of large-scale interannual and interdecadal climate modes and teleconnection patterns with two long-term integrations of the coupled general circulation model of ECHAM4/OPYC3 at the Max-Planck-Institute for Meteorology, Hamburg. One is the control (CTRL) run with fixed present-day concentrations of greenhouse gases. The other experiment is a simulation of transient greenhouse warming, named GHG run. In the GHG run the averaged geopotential height at 500 hPa is increased significantly, and a negative phase of the Pacific/North American (PNA) teleconnection-like distribution pattern is intensified. The standard deviation over the tropics (high latitudes) is enhanced (reduced) on the interdecadal time scales and reduced (enhanced) on the interannual time scales in the GHG run. Except for an interdecadal mode related to the Southern Oscillation (SO) in the GHG run, the spatial variation patterns are similar for different (interannual + interdecadal, interannual, and interdecadal) time scales in the GHG and CTRL runs, Spatial distributions of the teleconnection patterns on the interannual and interdecadal time scales in the GHG run are also similar to those in the CTRL run. But some teleconnection patterns show linear trends and changes of variances and frequences in the GHG run. Apart from the positive linear trend of the SO, the interdecadal modulation to the El Nino/SO cycle is enhanced during the GHG 2040 Ο 2099. This is the result of an enhancement of the Walker circulation during that period. La Nina events intensify and El Nino events relatively weaken during the GHG 2070 Ο 2090. It is interesting to note that with increasing greenhouse gas concentrations the relation between the SO and the PNA pattern is reversed significantly from a negative to a positive correlation on the interdecadal time scales and weakened on the interannual time scales. This suggests that the increase of the greenhouse gas concentrations will trigger the nonstationary correlation between the SO and the PNA pattern both on the interdecadal and interannual time scales.",,"annual variation; decadal variation; general circulation model; global warming; teleconnection",,,,,,"Bacher, A., (1998) Variability on Decadal Scales in Pacific Sea Surface Temperatures and Atmosphere Ocean Interaction in the Coupled Atmosphere-Sea Ice-Ocean General Circulation Model ECHAM4/ OPYC3, p. 139. , Ph D Dissertation, University of Hamburg, Hamburg, Germany; Bacher, A., Oberhuber, J.M., Roeckner, E., ENSO dynamics and seasonal cycle in the tropical Pacific as simulated by the ECHAM4/OPYC3 coupled general circulation model (1998) Clim. Dyn, 14, pp. 431-450; Barnett, T.P., Arpe, K., Bengtsson, L., Ji, M., Kumar, A., Potential predictability and AMIP implications of midlatitude climate variability in two general circulation models (1997) J. Clim, 10, pp. 2321-2329; Bengtsson, L., The climate response to the changing greenhouse gas concentration in the atmosphere (1996) NATO ASI Series, 144, pp. 293-332; Bengtsson, L., Arpe, K., Roeckner, E., Schulzweida, U., Climate predictability experiments with a general circulation model (1996) Clim. Dyn, 12, pp. 261-278; Bengtsson, L., Botzet, M., Esch, M., Will greenhouse gas-induced warming over the next 50 years lead to higher frequency and greater intensity of hurricanes? (1996) Tellus, 48 A, pp. 57-73; Broccoli, A.J., Lau, N.-C., Nath, M.J., The cold ocean-warm land pattern: Model simulation and relevance to climate change detection (1998) J. Clim, 11, pp. 2743-2763; Chen, W.Y., Fluctuations in Northern Hemisphere 700 mb height field associated with the Southern Oscillation (1982) Mon. Weather Rev, 110, pp. 808-823; Corti, S., Molteni, F., Palmer, T.N., Signature of recent climate change in frequencies of nature atmospheric circulation regimes (1999) Nature, 398, pp. 799-802; Grötzner, A., Latif, M., Barnett, T.P., A decadal climate cycle in the North Atlantic Ocean as simulated by the ECHO coupled GCM (1998) J. Clim, 11, pp. 831-847; Gu, D.F., Philander, S.G.H., Interdecadal climate fluctuations that depend on exchanges between the tropics and extratropics (1997) Science, 275, pp. 805-807; Hu, Z.-Z., Bengtsson, L., Stratospheric response to global warming in the Northern Hemisphere winter (2000) Tellus, , accepted; Hu, Z.-Z., Bengtsson, L., Arpe, K., Impact of global warming on the Asian winter monsoon in a coupled GCM (2000) J. Geophys. Res, 105, pp. 4607-4624; Hurrell, J.W., Influence of variations in extratropical wintertime teleconnections on Northern Hemisphere temperature (1996) Geophys. Res. Lett, 25, pp. 665-668; (1992) Climate Change 1992, the Supplementary Report to the IPCC Scientific Assessment, p. 198. , IPCC, Houghton J.T., Callander B.A., Varney S.K.V. (eds) Cambridge University Press, Cambridge, UK; (1994) Climate Change 1994: Radiative Forcing of Climate Change and an Evaluation of the IPCC IS92 Emission Scenarios, p. 339. , IPCC, Houghton